es, Rose explains why citizens are entitled to free time-time not committed to meeting life's necessities and instead available for chosen pursuits. The novel argument that the just society must guarantee all citizens their fair share of free time provides principled grounds to address critical policy choices, including work hours regulations, Sunday closing laws, public support for caregiving, and the pursuit of economic growth.Delving into an original topic that touches everyone, Free Time demonstrates why all citizens have, in the words of early labor reformers, a right to "hours for what we will."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLeisure. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aSunday closing laws.  aUnited States.  abasic needs.  acaregivers.  acaregiving.  acontemplation.  adistributive justice.  aeconomic growth.  aeffective freedoms.  aegalitarian justice.  aemployment.  afree choice.  afree time.  afreedom of association.  agender justice.  agender.  ahousehold responsibilities.  aincome.  ainequality.  ajust society.  alabor demand.  alabor regulations.  aleisure.  aliberal egalitarianism.  aliberal justice.  aliberal proceduralism.  amoney.  anecessary activities.  anecessary activity.  aoccupational choice.  apaid work.  aparents.  aplay.  arecreation.  aresources.  aresponsibility.  ashared free time.  aspecific goods.  awealth.  awelfare policies.  awork hours.  aworkers.  aworkplace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400883684zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400883684423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400883684.jpg  a978-3-1